# Introduction {.tabset}

## What is LASSO?

**LASSO** stands for **Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator**. It is a regularized regression technique that simultaneously performs:

1. **Coefficient estimation** — fitting a regression model to your data
2. **Variable selection** — automatically shrinking some coefficients to exactly zero, effectively removing irrelevant predictors

LASSO was introduced by [Robert Tibshirani (1996)](https://doi.org/10.1111/j.2517-6161.1996.tb02080.x) and has since become one of the most widely used methods in modern statistics and machine learning.

## The Core Idea

In **Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)**, we minimize the residual sum of squares:

$$\text{Minimize: } \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \beta_0 - \sum_{j=1}^{p}\beta_j x_{ij})^2$$

**LASSO** adds a penalty term — the sum of the absolute values of the coefficients, multiplied by a tuning parameter $\lambda$:

$$\text{Minimize: } \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \beta_0 - \sum_{j=1}^{p}\beta_j x_{ij})^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p}|\beta_j|$$

- When $\lambda = 0$: You get standard OLS
- As $\lambda \to \infty$: All coefficients are shrunk to zero
- The optimal $\lambda$ is chosen via **cross-validation**

