# Comparison with Other Methods

## Overview Table

| Feature                  | OLS / MLE        | Ridge Regression   | LASSO             | Elastic Net       |
|--------------------------|------------------|--------------------|-------------------|--------------------|
| **Penalty**              | None             | L2 ($\sum \beta_j^2$) | L1 ($\sum |\beta_j|$) | L1 + L2 combined  |
| **Variable Selection**   | No               | No                 | Yes               | Yes                |
| **Handles Multicollinearity** | Poorly     | Well               | Moderately        | Well               |
| **Bias**                 | Unbiased         | Biased             | Biased            | Biased             |
| **Variance**             | Can be high      | Lower              | Lower             | Lower              |
| **Best When**            | $n \gg p$, few predictors | Correlated predictors | Sparse models | Correlated + sparse |

## OLS / Maximum Likelihood Estimation

- Produces **unbiased** estimates under classical assumptions (normality, homoscedasticity, independence)
- Never sets a coefficient to zero — all predictors remain in the model
- Tends to **overfit** when the number of predictors is large relative to the sample size
- Low bias, but can have **high variance**

## Ridge Regression (L2 Penalty)

- Adds a penalty on the **squared** coefficients: $\lambda \sum \beta_j^2$
- Shrinks coefficients toward zero but **never exactly to zero**
- Handles **multicollinearity** well
- Does **not** perform variable selection

## LASSO (L1 Penalty)

- Adds a penalty on the **absolute** coefficients: $\lambda \sum |\beta_j|$
- Can shrink coefficients **exactly to zero** → automatic variable selection
- Introduces **bias** in exchange for reduced **variance** (the bias-variance tradeoff)
- May struggle with groups of highly correlated predictors (arbitrarily picks one)

## Elastic Net (L1 + L2 Combined)

- Combines both penalties: $\lambda_1 \sum |\beta_j| + \lambda_2 \sum \beta_j^2$
- Gets the **variable selection** of LASSO with the **grouping effect** of Ridge
- Particularly useful in psychology where predictor variables are often correlated (e.g., subscales of related constructs)

```{r penalty-visualization, fig.cap="Visualization of L1 (LASSO) vs L2 (Ridge) constraint regions"}
library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)

# Create constraint region plots
theta <- seq(0, 2 * pi, length.out = 300)

# L1 (LASSO) - Diamond
l1_x <- cos(theta)
l1_y <- sin(theta)
l1_r <- 1 / (abs(cos(theta)) + abs(sin(theta)))
l1_df <- data.frame(x = l1_r * cos(theta), y = l1_r * sin(theta))

# L2 (Ridge) - Circle
l2_df <- data.frame(x = cos(theta), y = sin(theta))

p1 <- ggplot(l1_df, aes(x, y)) +
  geom_polygon(fill = "#3498db", alpha = 0.3, color = "#2c3e50", linewidth = 1) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", alpha = 0.3) +
  coord_fixed() +
  labs(title = "L1 Constraint (LASSO)", x = expression(beta[1]), y = expression(beta[2])) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  annotate("text", x = 0.5, y = -0.8, label = "Corners touch axes\n→ coefficients = 0",
           size = 3.5, color = "#2c3e50")

p2 <- ggplot(l2_df, aes(x, y)) +
  geom_polygon(fill = "#e74c3c", alpha = 0.3, color = "#2c3e50", linewidth = 1) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", alpha = 0.3) +
  coord_fixed() +
  labs(title = "L2 Constraint (Ridge)", x = expression(beta[1]), y = expression(beta[2])) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  annotate("text", x = 0.5, y = -0.8, label = "Smooth boundary\n→ coefficients shrink but ≠ 0",
           size = 3.5, color = "#2c3e50")

grid.arrange(p1, p2, ncol = 2)
```

> **Why does LASSO set coefficients to zero but Ridge doesn't?** The diamond shape of the L1 constraint region has corners that sit on the axes. When the OLS solution's contour lines intersect this diamond, they're most likely to hit a corner — where one or more coefficients are exactly zero.

