# Select-Then-Refit Workflow

A common workflow in psychology: use LASSO for variable selection, then refit with OLS for interpretable estimates.

```{r select-refit}
# Get selected variables at lambda.1se
lasso_coefs <- coef(cv_fit, s = "lambda.1se")
selected <- rownames(lasso_coefs)[which(lasso_coefs != 0)]
selected <- selected[selected != "(Intercept)"]

cat("Selected predictors:\n")
cat(paste(" -", selected), sep = "\n")
```

```{r ols-refit}
# Refit with OLS using only the selected predictors
if (length(selected) > 0) {
  df_train <- data.frame(Therapy_Outcome = y_train, x_train)
  
  formula_selected <- as.formula(
    paste("Therapy_Outcome ~", paste(selected, collapse = " + "))
  )
  
  ols_refit <- lm(formula_selected, data = df_train)
  
  cat("\n=== OLS Refit on LASSO-Selected Variables ===\n\n")
  summary(ols_refit)
} else {
  cat("No predictors were selected at lambda.1se.\n")
}
```

> **Caveat:** The p-values and confidence intervals from this refitted model are **optimistic** because the variable selection step is not accounted for. This two-step procedure does not have the same inferential guarantees as a pre-specified OLS model. For valid post-selection inference, consider packages like `selectiveInference`.

