# Tuning Alpha for Elastic Net

When you have correlated predictors (common in psychology), tuning both $\alpha$ and $\lambda$ can improve results.

```{r tune-alpha, fig.cap="CV Error across different alpha values"}
alphas <- seq(0, 1, by = 0.1)
cv_errors <- sapply(alphas, function(a) {
  cv <- cv.glmnet(x_train, y_train, alpha = a)
  min(cv$cvm)
})

alpha_df <- data.frame(Alpha = alphas, CV_Error = cv_errors)

ggplot(alpha_df, aes(x = Alpha, y = CV_Error)) +
  geom_line(color = "#2c3e50", linewidth = 1.2) +
  geom_point(color = "#e74c3c", size = 3) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = alphas[which.min(cv_errors)], linetype = "dashed", color = "#3498db") +
  annotate("text",
    x = alphas[which.min(cv_errors)] + 0.05,
    y = max(cv_errors),
    label = paste("Best α =", alphas[which.min(cv_errors)]),
    hjust = 0, color = "#3498db", size = 4
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Cross-Validated Error Across Alpha Values",
    subtitle = "α = 0 (Ridge) ←→ α = 1 (LASSO)",
    x = "Alpha (mixing parameter)",
    y = "Cross-Validated MSE"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14)
```

